dialog_nodes.title: How long can I continue my COBRA coverage?

values.text: COBRA requires that continuation coverage extend from the date of the qualifying event for a limited period of 18 or 36 months. The length of time depends on the type of qualifying event that gave rise to 6 the COBRA rights. A plan, however, may provide longer periods of coverage beyond the maximum period required by law. When the qualifying event is the covered employee's termination of employment or reduction in hours of employment, qualified beneficiaries are entitled to 18 months of continuation coverage. When the qualifying event is the end of employment or reduction of the employee's hours, and the employee became entitled to Medicare less than 18 months before the qualifying event, COBRA coverage for the employee's spouse and dependents can last until 36 months after the date the employee becomes entitled to Medicare. For example, if a covered employee becomes entitled to Medicare 8 months before the date his/her employment ends (termination of employment is the COBRA qualifying event), COBRA coverage for his/her spouse and children would last 28 months (36 months minus 8 months). For more information on how entitlement to Medicare impacts the length of COBRA coverage, contact the Department of Labor's Employee Benefits Security Administration at askebsa.dol.gov or by calling 1-866-444-3272. For other qualifying events, qualified beneficiaries must be provided 36 months of continuation coverage.

dialog_nodes.title: Why do I have limited dental benefits?

values.text:
If you and/or your dependent(s) are not currently enrolled for dental coverage through Duke and enroll for 2021, you and/or your dependent(s) will be considered a "late entrant." As a "late entrant" your benefits during 2021 will be limited to preventive services: two preventive routine care exams (not including X-rays), two prophylaxis (routine) cleanings, and for children under age 19, one fluoride application. No other dental or orthodontia procedures or services will be covered during the first 12 months, if a member is enrolled as a late entrant.

Periodontal procedures, including maintenance/ cleanings, would not be covered during this 12-month period.

Once you have been enrolled in a Duke dental plan for at least 12 months, the plan will also cover basic and major procedures such as fillings, extractions, crowns, root canals and periodontal treatment (including periodontal maintenance which applies towards cleaning frequency).

This 12-month waiting period does not apply:

if you are switching from one Duke dental plan to another Duke plan,
if you enroll an eligible dependent within 30 days of a qualifying event such as marriage or adoption, or
if you add a child during an open enrollment period prior to his/her second birthday.

dialog_nodes.title: Add new spouse and any new dependents gained from marriage.

values.text: 1. Log into your Duke@Work Account My Benefits and select the qualifying life event enrollment link.
2. Select the life event reason "You got married and you want to add your spouse and/or new dependents to your health plans" from the drop-down list.
3. Select the effective date of your life event which is either the date of marriage or you can check the box for coverage to take effect the first of the month following your marriage.
4. Add your new spouse's and any new dependents' name, birth date, gender, SSN and their relationship to you.
5. Make your allowable changes; make sure you link any new dependents to your health plans.
6. Upload a copy of your marriage certificate as your supporting documentation.
7. Check & Submit your qualifying life event form for review and approval.

dialog_nodes.title: Add myself or other dependents to health plans lost due to divorce

values.text: 1. Log into your Duke@Work Account My Benefits and select the qualifying life event enrollment link.
2. Select the life event reason "You got divorced and you and eligible dependents lost coverage" from the drop-down list.
3. Select the effective date of your life event, which is the date you lost other group insurance coverage due to divorce (generally this is the date of divorce).
4. Add your dependents' name, birth date, gender, SSN, and their relationship to you, if they are not currently listed as dependents.
5. Make your allowable changes; make sure you link any new dependents to your health plans

6. Upload a copy of your COBRA enrollment notice,  employer document, on company letterhead, or other official document showing the names of previously covered dependents, the plans they were covered under, and the effective date they lost coverage under these plans.
7. Check & Submit your qualifying life event form for review and approval.

dialog_nodes.title: You want to add coverage due to loss of coverage under your deceased spouse

values.text: 1. Log into your Duke@Work Account My Benefits and select the qualifying life event enrollment link.
2. Select the life event reason "Death of a spouse and you are losing your coverage" from the drop-down list.
3. Select the effective date of your life event, which is the date you lost other group insurance coverage under your deceased spouse's plan (generally, the date of death).
4. Add your dependents' name, birth date, gender, SSN, and their relationship to you, if they are not currently listed as dependents.
5. Make your allowable changes; make sure you link any new dependents to your health plans.

6. Upload a copy of your COBRA enrollment notice,  employer document, on company letterhead, or other official document showing the names of previously covered dependents, the plans they were covered under, and the effective date they lost coverage under these plans.
7. Check & Submit your qualifying life event form for review and approval.

dialog_nodes.title: I want to drop my out of network medical plan

values.text: 1. Log into your Duke@Work Account My Benefits and select the qualifying life event enrollment link.

2. Select the life event reason "Out of network- You relocated & you are now outside your current coverage network (Use ONLY if new zip codes make you ineligible for current network)" from the drop-down list.
3. Select the effective date of your life event, which is the first of the month following the date of your relocation.
4. Select your dependent's name and medical plan that needs to be dropped

5. Upload a document confirming your dependent's new address such as a rental agreement or college admissions showing the address of the university they will be attending.  Employees should update their home address via Duke@Work for supporting documentation.
6. Check & Submit your qualifying life event form for review and approval.
